Today being the 43rd anniversary of the death of Getulio Vargas(1), I
thought
it was time for a TL about him. We can never have enough Brazilian
ATLs
on SHWI, which is all the more reason to come up with a scenario in
which
Vargas does not commit suicide in Rio's Catete Palace but holds on to
the Brazilian Presidency and does not &quot;leave life to enter history&quot;.

For one thing, the attempted assassination of Carlos Lacerda which
resulted in the death of an air force officer has already happened, so
the
military is enraged. The economy's already going to crap, furthering
discontent with his regime. I'm guessing a military coup is going to
happen with Vargas remaining President. The generals are waiting
in the lurch.

Effects? How long would military rule last? As long as the anos de
chumbo lasted (21 years)?Will some of the same principals behind
the 1964 coup be a part of the *1954 coup? Can we safely butterfly
away the political future of Joao Goulart (Minister of
Labor in the last Vargas government)? (OTOH, Kubitschek and
Quadros were both state governors at the time, not sure how
their futures would be affected). Is Ike as favorable towards a
military coup against Vargas as LBJ was towards OTL's coup
against Goulart? (I personally doubt it ; it would be quite difficult
depicting Vargas as a Communist. Then again, Mossadegh
was not a communist either...)

If military rule is short lived, will Vargas return to the presidency
or remain in exile? How is the Brazilian economy affected?

The one positive effect of TTL: no Brasilia. Does Rio remain
in better shape than it fell into in OTL with it remaining the
capital?

Any other effects?

Best,
Stan B.

(1) http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/24/newsid_454...
