I doubt it.  There were two factors present in 1964 that were not yet there a
decade earlier:

(1) One thing that strengthened hard-line views in the Brazilian military in
1964 was the idea that the military had been too tolerant in the past; after
Vargas' suicide it had allowed politics as usual to resume and Kubitschek
(with Vargasite support) to win in 1955; and again in 1961 after Quadros
resigned it had allowed the Vargasite left-populist Goulart to take office
under a compromise (establishing parliamentary government) that didn't last
long.  There was a feeling that &quot;we won't make the same mistake this time; we
are going to stay in power until we have transformed the system to our
liking.&quot;

(2) By 1964 the Cuban Revolution had greatly heightened the military's fear
of communism.

In 1954 I think that the military would try to restore constitutional
government fairly soon, with Vargas forced to leave the country. It is not
clear to me whether Kubitschek would be allowed to run for president.  OT1H
he was a member of the pro-Vargas Social Democratic Party; OTOH he was not as
objectionable to the military as a left-populist like Goulart (of Vargas' own
PTB or Brazilian Labor Party) who in this TL will almost certainly *not* be
allowed to run as Kubitschek's running mate.  Even if Kubitschek is elected
and takes office, he may not serve out his term if he tries to make deals
with the exiled Vargas and the more radical Vargasites like Goulart.  (There
is an analogy here with Argentina, where Frondizi was elected president in
1958 with Peronist support, and attempted to integrate Peronists into the
Argentine political system--something which he discovered could not be done
as long as Peron was still alive and determined to return, and the military
still opposed to any reconciliation with him.  Once Frondizi allowed the
Peronists to participate in the 1962 elections, a coup was almost
inevitable.)

