OTOH:

(1) &quot;April 15, 1955   The New Federal Capital Locating Commission (which had
been created in 1953) chooses the definitive location where Brasília will be
constructed - the 'Sítio Castanho'.  This of course was before Kubtischek was
electred (though shortly after he had promised to abide by the constitutional
provision calling  for moving the capital.)

(2)  &quot;Sep 19, 1956  Congress unanimously enacts the Bill (Law #2,874).&quot;
http://www.infobrasilia.com.br/bsb_h1i.htm#History

With the Commission having removed the excuse that &quot;we don't know just where
we want to locate the new capital&quot; and with the vote in Congress being
*unanimous* (granted that vote was in response to a presiential intiative but
it is at least indicative of the popularity of the idea since obviously many
of the members of Congress were not supporters of Kubitschek), it seems to me
at least plausible that Brasilia would have been created even had someone
else been president.  If there had been a lot of sentiment that &quot;we just
can't afford it right now&quot; I don't think the vote would have been unanimous.

I'll have to look up what Kubitschek's opponents said in 1955 about moving
the capital.  Incidentally, the race among the top three candidates was
fairly close:

Candidate (party) Popular vote (3 Oct 1955) [3]
Juscelino Kubitschek de Oliveira (Social Democratic) 3,077,411
Juarez do Nascimento Fernandes Távora (National Democratic) 2,610,462
Ademar Pereira de Barros (Social Progress Party) 2,222,725
Plínio Salgado (Popular Representation Party) 714,379
blank 161,852
void 310,185

http://www.archontology.org/nations/braz/braz_rep2/kubitschek.php

According to
http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,893060-2,00.html &quot;Also in
the race is a candidate who has no chance of winning but who could
conceivably influence the outcome by bowing out and tossing his support to
Távora. The sure loser, running under the banner of his own right-wing Party
of Popular Representation: Plinio (&quot;This is the Man&quot;) Salgado, 54, founder of
Brazil's prewar fascist-type Greenshirts.&quot;

So to prevent Kubitschek from becoming president in 1955, instead of having
Vargas live, we can have a later POD:  Plinio Salgado withdraws, and enough
of his vote goes to Tavora for the latter to win.  What then?  According to
*Time*:

&quot;General Juarez (&quot;Fight the Thieves and Hoodwinkers of the People&quot;) Távora,
56, favorite of army officers and intellectuals. Table-thumping Távora has an
odd assortment of parties behind him: the conservative National Democratic
Union, the anticlerical Socialists and the staunchly Roman Catholic Christian
Democrats.*

&quot;Doctors &amp; Actors. Brainy General Távora would undoubtedly win the presidency
if voters were counted only in the northeast, where he appeals both as a
native son (born in the state of Ceará) and as a man of principle and piety
(his cousin is the auxiliary bishop of Rio). Outside the northeast, Távora
has apparently failed to capture much working-class support, despite 1) his
promise to impose profit sharing on employers and 2) campaign help from one
of Brazil's most gifted demagogues, São Paulo Governor Janio Quadros, who
took a leave of absence to stump for Távora.&quot;

Tavora had been active in the *tenetismo* movement of the 1920s.
http://www.britannica.com/ebc/article-9099962 He broke with the most famous
of the tenentes, Luis Carlos Prestes, in 1930, when Prestes abandoned
reformism for communism.  Winning with the support of the military,
Catholics, intellectuals, Janio Quadros, and Plinio Salgado's supporters
would make Tavora the product of an even stranger coalition than the one that
supported him in  OTL, but Plinio Salgado's support would no more make Tavora
a fascist than the Communists' support of Kubitschek made Kubitschek a
Communist.

