Withycombe (citation below) covers that in her introduction.  Full
quotation below.  In brief: in English it's post-Reformation.  &quot;One of
the earliest examples noted is Lord Guildford Dudley, ... husband of
Lady Jane Grey, whose mother's maiden name was Guildford.&quot;

The other way, a given name appearing as a surname, happened
substantially earlier in English.  Reaney and Wilson, p. xxi et seq,
say that it starts becoming common &quot;in the early twelfth century&quot; but
adduce exampels from the mid 11th C.  &quot;The general opinion is that
such surnames are due to the dropping of 'filius' [son].&quot;, but &quot;It is
difficult to believe in this 'dropping of filius' theory. ... There
seems no alternative to regarding these forms [filius X, apparently]
as scribal descriptions.&quot;

However, as Mr. Rostrom noted, such patterns are not known in at least
some other cultures.  For example, in Irish and Scots Gaelic, when a
given name appears in a byname, it has to have a marker like &quot;mac&quot; or
&quot;{O'}&quot;.  Welsh &quot;ap&quot;.  Arabic similarly: patronymic like &quot;ibn&quot; or
&quot;bint&quot;, or child-o-nymic (?) like &quot;abu&quot;.  I don't know of Gaelic or
Welsh examples of surnames becoming given names, but I'm no expert.
Arabic has examples like &quot;Abdallah&quot; as given names.

I don't know enough to say that unmarked given names as surnames, or
surnames moving into given names, don't happen in *any* other
cultures, but that may not be what Mr. Rostrom meant.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This is from a discussion I was in about surnames moving to the given
name position in 16th C English.

E. G. Withycombe, _The Oxford Dictionary of English Christian Names_,
3rd ed., p. xli (N.B.: British &quot;christian name&quot; == American &quot;first
name&quot; == &quot;given name&quot;):

An interesting post-Reformation development was the use of
surnames as christian names.  One of the earliest examples noted
is Lord Guildford Dudley, son of the Duke of Northumberland and
husband of Lady Jane Grey, whose mother's maiden name was
Guildford.  Another early example was Sir Warham St. Leger
(1525-97), whose mother was d. and heiress of Hugh Warham, and
whose nephew was also named Warham St. Leger.  The fashion became
fairly general among the landed gentry in Elizabeth's time, and
apparently gave rise to some criticism.  Camden writes (1605):

'Whereas in late years Surnames have been given for Christian
names among us, and no where else in Christendome; although
many dislike it, for that great inconvenience will ensue:
nevertheless it seemeth to proceed from hearty good will, and
affection of the godfathers to shew their love, or from a
desire to continue &amp; propagate theoir own name to succeeding
ages.  And is in no wise to be disliked, but rather approved
in those, which matching with heirs generall of worshipfull
antient families, have given these names to their heirs, with
a mindful and thankful regard of them, as we have now,
Pickering Wotton, Grevill Varney, Bassingburne Gawdy, Calthorp
Parker, Pecsall Brocas, Fitz-Raulf Chamberlaine, who are the
heirs of Pickering, Bassingburne, Greville, Calthorp, &amp;c.' ...

The fashion was confined to the nobility and landed gentry until
the 19th century.

Ursula Whitcher looked at Camden's examples:

Pickering Wotton, Grevill Varney, Bassingburne Gawdy, Calthorp
Parker, Pecsall Brocas, Fitz-Raulf Chamberlaine

and noted that the given names were all place names, so far as she
could tell.

