Not all cultures have a tradition of inherited
surnames. Iceland of course has none. Arab countries
have developed some. I have read that the transitions
have been quite recent. Osama &quot;bin Laden&quot; is the
grandson of &quot;Laden&quot;; his father is Mohammed bin Awad
&quot;bin Laden&quot;, which has become a surname.

The practice of surname as given name is unknown in
hispanophone culture, except that Hispanophones sometimes
import surnames from _other_ cultures for use as given
names (baseball players Wilson Alvarez, Wilton Guerrero,
BronsonArroyo, Nelson Cruz). I have encountered two exceptions:

1) baseball player Beltran Perez (full name Beltran Ojilbio
Cruz Perez)

2) a supermarket checker whose namebadge read &quot;Cruz&quot;. (when
I asked, she said yes, it was her first name, and people
called her the lady with two last names - i.e. the
practice _is_ rare.)

I've never heard of a French, German, Italian,
Dutch, Russian, Swedish, or Polish example, and
only one Portuguese example (General Juarez Tavora
who inspired the thread).

I don't know enough about Japanese, Chinese, or
Indian cultures to address the issue.

Given names as surnames are not that unusual in other
Euro cultures, I think. There was a baseball player
named Felix José; Joseph Joachim (1831-1907) a Jewish-
Hungarian musician; Joseph &quot;Sepp&quot; Dietrich, an SS
general; Otto John, a German political and intelligence
figure of the 1950s; German engineer Nicolaus Otto;
French, Spanish, German, and Estonian Martins. I could
find more.

