Many of these are the names of familes who made a nuisance of
themselves in the Debatable lands that were controlled by neither
Scotland or England. The Armstrongs, for example,at the hieght of
their power could put 3,000 men in the saddle. James I &amp; VI attempted
to put a stop to that when he became head of both kingdoms, and it was
ont unknown for people to be hanged just for bearing a notorious
surname.

Many were deported to the Ulster Plantation and elsewhere. Today the
three most common surnames in County Fermanagh are Armstrong, Elliott
and Johnston, all Border surnames, and there are many more. The
practise of naming a boy byhis mother's maiden name is very common
locally, but seems to beconfined to the surnames with Border origins.

The Elliotts are an odd exception. There are apparently more than 70
ways of spelling the name in Scotland, but the Fermanagh spelling of
double L and double T is unknown there, and I know of no one with
Elliott as a given name.

BTW, is there any record of &quot;Clive&quot; as a given name before the fame of
Clive ofIndia?
